+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GDq4xhVd3SmRJR2o5cbZve","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Found the root cause of the remaining 2 failures.**\n\nThe `EventBus` uses a **module-level `globalHandlers` map** (`const globalHandlers: Map<string, EventHandler[]> = new Map()`). This is shared across ALL test instances. When `beforeEach` creates a new `EventBus`, it doesn't clear the global handlers. So across test runs, handlers accumulate.\n\nThe \"releases stock on order.cancelled\" test runs after \"rolls back partial reservations on failure\" which registered handlers. The second `ORDER_EVENTS.CREATED` emission goes to ALL previously registered handlers from prior tests — including handlers from a `InventoryService` with a **different** (empty) repository. Those handlers fail because stock is 0 in the old repos.\n\nSimilarly for \"reserves stock for concurrent orders independently\" — by the time this test runs, there are multiple `handleOrderCreated` handlers registered (from all previous `beforeEach` calls), and some fire against repos with no stock.\n\nThe fix: the `EventBus.clear()` method exists but isn't being called between tests. The tests call `service.registerHandlers()` but never call `bus.clear()`. However, we can't modify tests. \n\nThe real bug is in the `EventBus` design: `globalHandlers` should be **instance-level**, not module-level. Each `EventBus` instance should have its own handlers map."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1284,"cache_read_input_tokens":45957,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1284},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bd1c5f3f-cb8e-4eca-b4a2-66b7caaac9fd","uuid":"7d0a81ed-1e76-4c82-8f1a-95813f5ba67f"}
